habitat_description:
Southwest:
The distribution of the Colorado chipmunk is central and southern Colorado, northern and central New Mexico, and northeastern Arizona (Best et al. 1994).  Inhabits rocky, broken terrain in open woodlands and shrublands, mostly in foothills and canyons (Fitzgerald et al. 1994).  At lower elevations can be found in pinon-juniper woodlands and montane shrublands and higher elevations they are found in montane forests (Fitzgerald et al. 1994).  Colorado chipmunks are in ponderosa pine forests, mixed coniferous forest and woodlands (Findley et al. 1975).  Can also be found in spruce-fir areas and scattered pinon-juniper woodland, especially if rockcrops are available (Findley et al. 1975).  Hoffmeister (1986) states they are associated with p-j woodland but can be found as high as rock outcrops in spruce-fir forests and rock outcrops surrounded by brush at the lower end of yellow pines. Food habits include seeds and fruits of various woody and herbaceous plants, and some insects (NatureServe). Feeds mainly on the ground, but obtains some food by climbing into trees and shrubs (NatureServe). Stores food in underground caches (NatureServe). Overwinter survival rate is less than 33%; local extirpation or near-extirpation is a common event (Best et al. 1994).  In Arizona, T. quadrivittatus is found from 1,800 to 2,700m (Cockrum 1960).  In southern Colorado, reaches elevations of 3,200m, and along the Front Range occur mostly below 2,130m (Fitzgerald et al. 1994).  Throughout its range, found at elevations of 1380-3360m (Best et al. 1994). This species is most closely associated with conifers and occurs at all elevations where conifers exist (Best et al. 1994).
